The world born of September 11
NEW YORK – This week marks the 20th anniversary of the terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001, in the United States.
On that day, 19 terrorists had taken control of four civil aircraft, crashed two of the planes into the towers of the World Trade Center in New York, hit the Pentagon with a third, and then led to the crash of a fourth plane in Pennsylvania after several passengers physically prevented the terrorists from reaching their target, which many believe was the White House or another American government building in Washington, DC.
All the hijackers were from the Middle East, and 15 from Saudi Arabia.
All had been trained in Afghanistan, and four in American flight schools, as part of a planned, organized, and carried out operation by Al-Qaeda (the "base"), a terrorist group led by Osama bin Laden.
At the end of the day, 2,977 innocent men, women, and children were killed, and more than 6,000 were injured.
Most were Americans, although citizens from more than a hundred other countries also lost their lives.
Many at the time feared that September 11 would usher in an era defined by global terrorism.
Indeed, other attacks carried out by Al-Qaeda followed, including several bombings on Madrid trains in March 2004, and then the attack carried out on London's public transport system in July 2005.
Terrorists who pledged allegiance to the Islamic State (IS) also killed 32 people at Brussels airport in March 2016, and carried out a series of smaller attacks (often using vehicles to strike pedestrians).
For all that, neither the United States nor any of their allies have ever suffered an attack of a magnitude comparable to those of September 11 – which are incomparable.
It is therefore appropriate to ask: Beyond the immediate losses, what difference has September 11 made?
Has history changed and, if so, to what extent?
Many reasons explain why terrorists have not managed to carry out other major attacks.
After the American invasion of Afghanistan, Al-Qaeda lost its sanctuary.
Nearly all governments in the world have put in place control procedures making it more difficult for potential terrorists to access airports and airplanes.
States have significantly strengthened their intelligence, police, and military capabilities in order to minimize risks and counter threats.
They have also developed mutual cooperation, terrorism being one of the few areas in which states often in disagreement are willing and ready to work together to a significant extent.
There is now also a broad consensus on what constitutes terrorism – the use of armed force by individuals and groups against civilians for political purposes – as well as a degree of support for the principle that governments should not make a distinction between terrorists and those who give them sanctuary and support.
The era is over when individuals and groups willing to kill in the name of their cause were romanticized as freedom fighters.
It is not to claim that terrorism has ceased to take the lives of tens of thousands of people every year.
Nevertheless, almost all attacks occur in the Middle East, Africa, and South Asia within the context of current conflicts (primarily in Iraq, Syria, Afghanistan, Libya, Somalia, Nigeria, Pakistan, and Yemen), as opposed to isolated attacks of the 9/11 type against major powers.
Terrorism is becoming increasingly localized and decentralized.
It is also resilient: the capture or elimination of a terrorist organization leader does not necessarily mean the end of the group.
Al-Qaeda, for example, survived the elimination of Ben Laden by American special forces in Pakistan, nearly ten years after the 9/11 attacks.
It is therefore not surprising that terrorism persists, without resolution of the problem in sight.
The possibility of a new September 11 cannot be ruled out either, although the American government has recently stated that the « most urgent terrorist threat » to the country exists domestically.
As the Provisional Irish Republican Army formulated after its failed attempt to assassinate British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher in 1984, « Today, we were not lucky, but remember that it only takes us to be lucky once.
You will always need to be lucky ».
The danger lies in the fact that one day, terrorists will get their hands on nuclear material, or will manage to manufacture and use a biological or chemical weapon, in which case terrorism could determine the era.
For now, this is not the case.
September 11th nonetheless marked a historic turning point, with a profound impact on American foreign policy over the last 20 years.
Although the attacks did not lead to an era of global terrorism, they indeed triggered the famous global war on terror, with major consequences on the behavior of the United States around the world, America's image in the eyes of the world, and the way many Americans eventually came to view their country's foreign policy.
The saga began in Afghanistan.
Shortly after the September 11th attacks, the United States offered the Taliban, who then controlled the Afghan government, a choice: hand over the Al-Qaeda officials about to leave the country, who were guilty of organizing the September 11th attacks, or risk their rule.
After the Taliban refused to hand over Al-Qaeda leaders, American intelligence and military personnel collaborated with an unstructured confederation of Afghan tribes, called the Northern Alliance, to overthrow the Taliban.
The United States contributed to the formation of a successor government that took control of most of the country.
This control was however never total or uncontested.
Many individuals loyal to the Taliban and Al-Qaeda sought refuge in the neighboring Pakistan, where they gradually regained strength as well as their military operations against the government that had replaced them.
On their part, the United States did not sufficiently work to build an Afghan army, reduce corruption, and deprive the Taliban of sanctuary in Pakistan.
Instead, America reinforced its own presence and military operations in Afghanistan, becoming essentially a partner of the government in its civil war.
At its peak, the US intervention in Afghanistan mobilized more than 100,000 American soldiers.
Over more than twenty years, the cost of the operations amounted to more than 2,000 billion dollars, with more than 2,300 American lives lost, and several tens of thousands among Afghans.
The effort was both excessive and insufficient.
The American presence deprived the Afghan government of much of its legitimacy, and sparked opposition against the United States, while the Taliban proved more resilient than America, which in 2020 had lost all will to fight in a conflict destined only to result in an indefinite stalemate.
The worldwide war against terrorism has also led the United States to go to war in Iraq.
The question remains open as to whether President George W. Bush would have taken military action if September 11 had not occurred.
The attacks certainly reinforced his tendency to want to signal to the world that the United States was not, as President Richard Nixon had formulated during the Vietnam War, a "helpless and pitiable giant."
This led some members of the administration (most notably Vice President Dick Cheney) to refuse the risk of seeing terrorists acquire weapons of mass destruction, which Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein apparently possessed (which ultimately was not the case) according to most protagonists.
Others intended to spread democracy in Iraq, and then throughout the entire Middle East, considering that this approach was not only feasible, but would also make the region much less likely to produce terrorists and support them.
Launched in March 2003, the war in Iraq did not unfold as the Bush administration and many members of Congress (including Joe Biden, then a senator) and world leaders who had approved it had wished or anticipated.
The United States was not prepared for most of the events that were to follow.
The initial military victories had indeed enabled the removal of the government, but quickly gave way to widespread unrest and a violent civil war.
The decision to disband the Iraqi army, and to exclude numerous Iraqis associated with the previous regime from government jobs, worsened an already chaotic situation.
More fundamentally, Iraq, like Afghanistan, demonstrated the limits of what military force can achieve at a reasonable cost and within reasonable timeframes.
Ultimately, the United States was forced to strengthen its military presence, bringing it to nearly 170,000 soldiers, in order to preserve the besieged successor government in Baghdad.
A certain degree of stability has been achieved, but at a considerable cost.
The United States has spent in Iraq at least as much as in Afghanistan, but with a much heavier human toll: more than 4,000 American soldiers killed, a far greater number wounded, and a rising rate of suicide among American military personnel (from both Iraq and Afghanistan).
This total also excludes deaths among private contractors and Iraqis, for whom estimates vary widely, but whose numbers certainly reach into the hundreds of thousands.
The war in Iraq has also weakened the United States in other respects.
No evidence has ever proven Iraq's involvement in the September 11 attacks, and America's reputation suffered when the argument for a military intervention without UN approval—aimed at eliminating Saddam's weapons of mass destruction—was revealed to be based on no real foundation.
Images of American soldiers mistreating Iraqi prisoners further tarnished the country's reputation.
Furthermore, an Iraq at war with itself has become synonymous with an emerging Iran as the most powerful country in the region (or one of the two most powerful if Israel is considered).
Since the war, Iran has strengthened its influence over Iraq, Syria, Yemen, and Lebanon.
Iraq and Afghanistan have also proven to be two major strategic distractions.
While the United States were deeply involved in the Middle East and South Asia, regions lacking major present powers and economic dynamism, the geopolitical balance has shifted against the United States, both in Europe and East Asia, due to the emergence of a more aggressive Russia, as well as a stronger and more assertive China.
The global war on terrorism could not and did not provide the United States with a compass in their approach to foreign policy regarding a renewed rivalry between major powers.
The wars conducted after September 11 also led to significant internal consequences for the United States.
They have shaken confidence in a country that had emerged from the Cold War with historically unprecedented preponderant power, and have undermined the national unity that had emerged immediately after the attacks.
The costs and failures associated with these wars have further fueled opposition to a major and lasting global role for the United States, giving rise to a new isolationist trend.
Similarly, this warrior tendency, associated with the global financial crisis of 2007-2009 and its economic repercussions, has seriously impacted the confidence of Americans in the elites, thus fueling the rise of a populist sentiment which, among other consequences, contributed to the rise to power of Donald Trump.
Today's America is more divided than ever internally, and less and less disposed to carry out this form of active foreign policy that characterized it since the end of World War II, and which overall greatly benefited Americans as well as many others.
With the benefit of hindsight, we can today consider September 11 as a harbinger of what was to come: less the globalization of terrorism than the fears of globalization.
The attacks conveyed the message that distance and borders mattered little in the global era.
Nothing remains local for long anymore, whether it be terrorists born in the Middle East and trained in Afghanistan, or the effects of a global financial crisis whose origins lie in poor American financial management.
We are all currently facing a pandemic virus that has killed several million people since its emergence in China in December 2019.
The fires, droughts, floods, storms, and heatwaves devastating many regions of the world are the consequence of climate change, itself a cumulative effect of human activity that releases unsustainable quantities of heat-trapping greenhouse gases into the atmosphere.
The era initiated by recent events comes to close a cycle, marking the 20th anniversary of the American intervention in the country.
Twenty years ago, the Taliban were quickly ousted from power; in recent weeks, they have just as easily regained it.
It is too early to know whether the Taliban will resume their old habits by once again becoming a sanctuary for terrorism, and whether terrorists around the world will boast of their victory over America and its allies.
What we do know, on the other hand, is that terrorism remains a characteristic of our world.
It will not define the future, but will remain one of the visible aspects of a globalization that already determines it.
